Title: Analysis of Heart Disease Risk Factors Dataset

Author: "Mohammad Hajjaj"

Date: 2024-07-29

1) Introduction :

Heart disease remains a predominant cause of illness and death globally. Recognizing the risk factors associated with heart disease is crucial for early detection, prevention, and management. This study uses a dataset from Kaggle, containing demographic, lifestyle, and medical information, to explore and analyze the factors contributing to heart disease. By examining these variables, we aim to identify significant predictors and understand their interactions, thereby enhancing clinical decision-making and patient outcomes.

2) Dataset Description :

2.1. Source of the Dataset.

The dataset utilized in this analysis is an open-source resource available on Kaggle. It is designed to assist researchers and clinicians in understanding heart disease risk factors. This dataset provides comprehensive information on individuals, including demographic details, lifestyle habits, medical history, and symptoms associated with heart disease.

2.2 Columns and Variables:

The dataset includes the following variables:

  • Age: Age of the individual (years).
  • Gender: Gender of the individual (Male/Female).
  • Cholesterol: Cholesterol level in mg/dL.
  • Blood Pressure: Systolic blood pressure in mmHg.
  • Heart Rate: Heart rate in beats per minute.
  • Smoking: Smoking status (Never/Former/Current).
  • Alcohol Intake: Alcohol intake frequency (None/Moderate/Heavy).
  • Exercise Hours: Hours of exercise per week.
  • Family History: Family history of heart disease (Yes/No).
  • Diabetes: Diabetes status (Yes/No).
  • Obesity: Obesity status (Yes/No).
  • Stress Level: Stress level on a scale of 1 to 10.
  • Blood Sugar: Fasting blood sugar level in mg/dL.
  • Exercise Induced Angina: Presence of exercise-induced angina (Yes/No).
  • Chest Pain Type: Type of chest pain experienced (Typical Angina/Atypical Angina/Non-anginal Pain/Asymptomatic).
  • Heart Disease: Target variable indicating the presence of heart disease (0: No, 1: Yes).

3) Literature Summary:

Extensive research has been conducted to understand the various risk factors contributing to heart disease. Demographic factors such as age and gender, lifestyle habits like smoking and alcohol intake, and medical history, including cholesterol levels, blood pressure, and diabetes, are well-documented in the literature as significant contributors to heart disease. Recent advancements in data analysis have enhanced the precision of heart disease prediction models, incorporating machine learning techniques and large datasets to provide deeper insights into risk factors and their interactions.

4) Research Questions:

Can we accurately predict risk of heart attack using patients' demographics, comorbidities, and other life style factors?

5) Unmet Clinical Need:

Despite the wealth of information available, there remains a critical need for comprehensive models that integrate various risk factors to predict heart disease accurately. Identifying the most significant predictors and understanding their interactions can aid in developing better prevention strategies and personalized treatment plans, ultimately reducing the burden of heart disease.

6) Data Analysis Steps:

We are going to perform the folloing steps to adress this resarche Qusition:

  1. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA): Visualize relationships between variables and the target.
  2. Descriptive Statistics: Summarize the key characteristics of the dataset.
  3. Data Cleaning: Handle missing values, outliers, and ensure data consistency.
  4. Model Building: Develop predictive models using techniques such as logistic regression Naive Bayes,,SVMs Decision Tree, Random Forest, Neural Network..
  5. Model Evaluation: Assess model performance using metrics like accuracy, precision, recall, a d AUC-R and the Lift Curve.C.

1.3 EDA for continuous variables

In[21]:
continuous_columns = ['Age', 'Cholesterol', 'Blood Pressure', 'Heart Rate', 'Exercise Hours', 'Stress Level', 'Blood Sugar']

for col in continuous_columns:
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

   
    skewness = df[col].skew()
    distribution_type = "Kurtosis" if abs(skewness) < 0.5 else "Skewed"

    
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    sns.histplot(df[col], kde=True, color='red', bins=30)
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.ylabel('Density')
    plt.title(f'Histogram for {col} ({distribution_type})')

    # Boxplot
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    sns.boxplot(y=df[col])
    plt.title(f'Boxplot of {col}')
    
  
    median = df[col].median()
    median_percentage = (median - df[col].min()) / (df[col].max() - df[col].min()) * 100
    
    plt.text(0, median, f'Median: {median:.2f} ({median_percentage:.2f}%)', 
             horizontalalignment='center', 
             verticalalignment='center', 
             fontsize=12, color='white', weight='bold',
             bbox=dict(facecolor='black', alpha=0.6))

    # Show the plot
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    # Sort the probabilities and true labels based on probabilities
    sorted_indices = np.argsort(y_pred_prob)[::-1]
    sorted_true_labels = np.array(y_test)[sorted_indices]

    # Calculate cumulative gains
    total_positives = np.sum(y_test)
    cumulative_positives = np.cumsum(sorted_true_labels)
    cumulative_lift = cumulative_positives / total_positives


    population_percentage = np.arange(1, len(y_test) + 1) / len(y_test) * 100


    plt.plot(population_percentage, cumulative_lift, color=color, label=f'{model_name}')

Performs a permutation test for the difference in AUCs

In[106]:
def permutation_auc_test(y_test, Random_Forest_probabilities, Neural_Network_probabilities, n_permutations=1000):
    """Performs a permutation test for the difference in AUCs."""
    observed_auc1 = roc_auc_score(y_test, Random_Forest_probabilities)
    observed_auc2 = roc_auc_score(y_test, Neural_Network_probabilities)
    observed_difference = observed_auc1 - observed_auc2

    permuted_differences = []

    for i in range(n_permutations):
      
        permuted_labels = np.random.permutation(y_test)

        
        auc1 = roc_auc_score(permuted_labels, Random_Forest_probabilities)
        auc2 = roc_auc_score(permuted_labels, Neural_Network_probabilities)

    
        permuted_differences.append(auc1 - auc2)

    
    p_value = np.mean(np.abs(permuted_differences) >= np.abs(observed_difference))

    return observed_difference, p_value


observed_diff, p_value = permutation_auc_test(y_test, Random_Forest_probabilities, Neural_Network_probabilities)

print(f'Observed difference in AUCs: {observed_diff:.3f}')
print(f'Permutation test p-value: {p_value:.4f}')

if p_value < 0.05:
    print("The difference between the AUCs is statistically significant.")
else:
    print("The difference between the AUCs is not statistically significant.")

Observed difference in AUCs: 0.021
Permutation test p-value: 0.3700
The difference between the AUCs is not statistically significant.

Statistical comparison between ROC-AUC between the best 2 classifiers

This means that there is no preference in which one to use when it comes to selecting best classifiers, both models have equal performance.
